<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-039-708  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 039 708.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 12 1990 n1341* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Motorola, TRW reckon their CPUAX RISC superchip is technology evenJapan does not have. (Motorola Inc. and TRW Inc.)andO;(reduced-instruction-set computing)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (product development)TRW Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    TRW; MOT.andO;Product:   TRW CPUAX SuperChip (microprocessor) (product development).andO;Topic:     MicroprocessorsProduct DevelopmentReduced-Instruction-Set ComputersDigital Signal ProcessingMilitaryProcessor SpeedJapanese Competition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOTOROLA, TRW RECKON THEIR CPUAX RISC SUPERCHIP ISandM;TECHNOLOGY EVEN JAPAN DOES NOT HAVEandM;The CPUAX SuperChip developed by Motorola Inc of Schaumburg, Illinois and TRWInc of Cleveland and designed to serve at the heart of advanced digitalsignal processing systems contains 4m transistors on a 2.1 square inchdevice, can process 200m floating point operations per second and can repairitself, the partners claim (CI No 1,336).andP;  The device, which is a RISC,implements an original architecture and is not compatible with any currentdevices.andP;  To activate the self-repair capability, the SuperChip will be wiredto a satellite chip which keeps tabs on its inner workings, and if a flawoccurs it will automatically switch in spare circuits on the chip and switchout the ones that have failed, without the user being aware of the problem.andO;A macrocell is an individual CPUAX building block, each being a stand-aloneelectronic device.andP;  The SuperChip is claimed to be the largest, most densechip in the world, and is fabricated to 0.5 micron design rules where currentleading edge parts such as 4M-bit memory chips are to design rules of justunder one micron.andP;  It is intended to be used as a central processor in arange of space and defence systems, such as in spacecraft or in the nosecones of missiles or fighters where high speed, small size and greatcomputing power and reliability are needed, but Motorola also sees it beingused in commercial applications in the future.andP;  TRW will be making the chipfor the US Navy later this year, but the chip isn't expected to make its wayonto the commercial market for the next couple of years as Motorola still hasto develop completely new production technologies to keep factory lines cleanenough to create the chips and new techniques for etching the tiny circuits.andO;Hector Ruiz, Motorola senior vice-president, expects it to be used in desktopsupercomputers and other equipment, with applications such as computer-aideddesign, medical diagnosis, plant process control and complex imaging.andP;  Hebelieves that the main benefit is that it gives Motorola technologies thatthe Japanese don't yet have.andO;</TEXT></DOC>